Durban - “It’s better to have the skills and not need them than to not know how to do it and need the skills.”
This was the sentiments expressed by Barry Mohan, training manager at Crisis Medical.

Mohan was speaking to the Daily News during National Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation (CPR) Week, which takes place from November 4 - 10 annually.
Cardiopulmonary resuscitation or CPR is an emergency procedure. It is performed in an effort to manually preserve intact brain function until further measures are taken to restore spontaneous blood circulation and breathing in a person who is in cardiac arrest.


 







